Scoping Review: The Intersection of Socioeconomic Status (SES) and Oral Expressive Language Development (OEL)

Main page

Danielle Jones
University of Oregon
March 2024

Scoping Review Rationale

More than 15% of children in the United States live in poverty. Children from low socioeconomic (SES) backgrounds are almost twice as likely to have a disability than children living above the poverty threshold. Children from low SES backgrounds often face early delays in communication development, which can negatively affect their cognitive and emotional development, academic success, and health outcomes throughout the lifespan.

The birth to 5-years-old window has been identified as a crucial time for oral language development. During the periods of infancy and early childhood, childrens brains experience rapid growth and development that lay the foundational framework for their language learning and cognitive capacities. Within this period, children progress from babbling at around 6 months, to uttering their first word around 12 months, and progress to developing a complete speech sound system and constructing complex sentences by the time they reach 5-6 years old. Delays and disorders in communication development are seen in approximately 8% of children in the United States, with language development being impacted by many environmental factors, including SES. For children from low SES backgrounds, delays in language development can be seen as early as 18-months of age. This is concerning as oral expressive language (OEL) proficiencies, such as vocabulary and grammar skills, are reliable predictors of later reading ability and academic achievement, indicating that early deficits in language skills can have a lasting impact on a childs academic and later life success.

Reporting of Disability Status

This bar graph shows how often researchers provided information on their participants disability status in the articles included in the scoping review. What is most interesting is that while researchers did indicate that their participants had a disability, the overwhelming majority of researchers did not indicate what kind of disability their participants had. This means that the majority of articles published about SES and OEL had the confounding factor of disability!
